<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-angles-substended-by-the-same-arc" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Angles Substended by the Same Arc</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.2 Angle Properties of a Circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Relate the angle subtended by an arc at the centre and at the circumference
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->
     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    20 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To use physical, dynamic modeling to visually and tactilely discover the Angle at the Centre Theorem and the Angles in the Same Segment Theorem.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Facilitate material distribution. Guide groups to keep their baseline rubber band anchored at the same two "boundary pins" while they stretch their "circumference bands" to different points on the rim. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="act-dynamic-circle-geoboard">
        <statement>
            <!-- <p><strong>Learner Experience: The Elastic Circle Investigation</strong></p>
             -->
            <p><term>Work in Groups:</term></p>
            <p>
                This activity must be carried out in collaborative learning groups of 3 to 4 students. Allocate roles within your group: 
                <ul>
                    <li><p><strong>The Builder:</strong> Manipulates the board, pins, and bands.</p></li>
                    <li><p><strong>The Measurer:</strong> Uses the protractor to read angles accurately.</p></li>
                    <li><p><strong>The Scribe:</strong> Records coordinates, angles, and group observations.</p></li>
                    <li><p><strong>The Presenter:</strong> Explains the group's findings to the rest of the class.</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p><term>Materials Needed:</term></p>
            <p>
                Each group will require the following local materials:
                <ul>
                    <li><p>One circular wooden board or thick piece of cardboard (minimum 30 cm diameter).</p></li>
                    <li><p>12 push-pins or small nails spaced evenly around the perimeter of the circle (representing hours on a clock face), plus 1 pin pushed firmly into the exact center <m>O</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>3 elastic rubber bands of different colors (or non-stretchy colored strings and paperclips).</p></li>
                    <li><p>A standard 180-degree protractor.</p></li>
                    <li><p>A ruler or straight-edge.</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p><term>Step-by-Step Practical Investigation:</term></p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Place your board flat on the desk. Select two perimeter pins at the bottom of the board to be your anchor points, <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> (for example, the "5 o'clock" and "7 o'clock" positions). 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         Take your first rubber band (Color 1). Stretch it from pin <m>A</m>, around the center pin <m>O</m>, and back to pin <m>B</m>. This forms the central angle <m>\angle AOB</m>. Measure this angle using your protractor and record it.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         Take your second rubber band (Color 2). Stretch it from the same anchor pin <m>A</m>, all the way to a pin <m>P</m> on the upper opposite side of the circle (e.g., the "12 o'clock" position), and back down to anchor pin <m>B</m>. Measure the angle <m>\angle APB</m> at pin <m>P</m> and record it.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         Divide the measurement of the central angle by the circumference angle:
                    </p>
                    <md>\text{Ratio} = \frac{\angle AOB}{\angle APB}</md>
                    <p>
                        What whole number does this ratio approximate?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                         Take your third rubber band (Color 3). Stretch it from <m>A</m>, to a different upper pin <m>Q</m> (e.g., the "2 o'clock" position), and back to <m>B</m>. Measure the angle <m>\angle AQB</m>. What do you notice when you compare the value of <m>\angle AQB</m> with <m>\angle APB</m>?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <p><term>Group Discussion and Reporting Questions:</term></p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        How does the "slackness" or "sharpness" of the rubber band triangle change physically as you stretch it to the center versus stretching it to the far boundary?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Formulate a general rule describing what happens to the angle at the boundary when the vertex point slides from one boundary pin to another, while staying anchored on the same baseline arc <m>AB</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
    </activity>
     

